SIMPLE: whiff
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whiff
<hw>Whiff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>weffe</ets>
vapor, whiff, probably of imitative origin; cf. Dan. <ets>vift</ets> a
puff, gust, W. <ets>chwiff</ets> a whiff, puff.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A sudden expulsion of air from the mouth; a quick
puff or slight gust, as of air or smoke.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But with the <qex>whiff</qex> and wind of his fell sword⟦br⟧
The unnerved father falls.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The skipper, he blew a <qex>whiff</qex> from his pipe,⟦br⟧
And a scornful laugh laughed he.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A glimpse; a hasty view.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The marysole, or sail
fluke.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whiff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Whiff
<hw>Whiff</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Whiffed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Whiffing</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To throw out in whiffs; to consume in whiffs; to
puff.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To carry or convey by a whiff, or as by a whiff; to
puff or blow away.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Old Empedocles, . . . who, when he leaped into Etna, having a dry,
sear body, and light, the smoke took him, and <qex>whiffed</qex> him up
into the moon.</q> <rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whiff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Whiff
<hw>Whiff</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To emit whiffs, as of smoke; to
puff.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whiffet</ent>⟦br⟧
